<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,190,1268]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,816,842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Habitat:—</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[393,443,817,843]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
population of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zidarova &amp; Kopalová &amp; Vijver" authorityYear="2012" box="[615,1005,817,842]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="australoschoenfelderi">
<emphasis box="[615,1005,817,842]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia australoschoenfelderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was sampled from the sandy bottom of a small pool near the southern beaches on Byers Peninsula, with an almost circumneutral pH (7.2) and a low specific conductance (&lt;100 µS/cm) value. The species was also found on Hurd Peninsula, usually rare but more abundant in soil under wet moss vegetations and among wet mosses surrounding shallow pools.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,190,1268]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,372,971,997]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the geographic distribution of the species (Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[1324,1426,972,997]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">australis</emphasis>
’ meaning southern) and to its similarity to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krammer" authorityYear="1992" box="[642,934,1010,1035]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="schoenfelderi">
<emphasis box="[642,934,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia schoenfelderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,190,1268]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,403,1048,1074]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Observations:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zidarova &amp; Kopalová &amp; Vijver" authorityYear="2012" box="[403,801,1049,1074]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="australoschoenfelderi">
<emphasis box="[403,801,1049,1074]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia australoschoenfelderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krammer" authorityYear="1992" box="[1106,1301,1049,1074]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="schoenfelderi">
<emphasis box="[1106,1301,1049,1074]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">P. schoenfelderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the latter differs in having a higher stria density (
<quantity box="[608,711,1088,1114]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.683" metricValueMax="4.064" metricValueMin="3.302" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="in" value="14.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="13.0">13–16 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[718,795,1088,1114]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
vs. 
<quantity box="[841,944,1088,1114]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" metricValueMax="3.048" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="in" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[951,1028,1088,1114]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
) giving the species a finer striation pattern. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reichardt" authorityYear="1985" box="[248,566,1127,1152]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="frauenbergiana">
<emphasis box="[248,566,1127,1152]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia frauenbergiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has even more striae per 
<quantity box="[873,950,1126,1152]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
(18–22 vs. 
<quantity box="[1092,1197,1126,1152]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" metricValueMax="3.048" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="in" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[1205,1287,1126,1152]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krasske" authorityYear="1932" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more irregular striation pattern with a clear shift in stria direction halfway between the central area and apices. 
<taxonomicName authority="Krammer (2000: 51)" authorityName="Krammer" authorityPageNumber="51" authorityYear="2000" box="[349,907,1204,1230]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="obscuriformis">
<emphasis box="[349,651,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="18">Pinnularia obscuriformis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K." box="[660,907,1204,1230]" pageId="7" pageNumber="18" refId="ref15524" refString="Krammer, K. (2000) The genus Pinnularia. In: H. Lange-Bertalot (ed.), Diatoms of Europe, Diatoms of the European Inland waters and comparable habitats. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag K. G., 1: 703 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krammer (2000: 51)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has comparable dimensions but more linear valves with acutely rounded apices.
</paragraph>
